pr_body:
Fix some behavior that annoyed me while using this package as a library.
Basically, I want to be able to control what is emitted and how as to allow proper integration in tools such as pure command line executables or tasks integrated with sentry & co.

With these changes, you would need to configure Ghost.py with something like this to get the session ID like you wanted to do in `ghost.logger`:
```python
    logging.config.dictConfig({
        'version': 1,
        'disable_existing_logger': True,
        'formatters': {
            'default': {
                'format': '%(asctime)s %(levelname)-8s %(name)-15s %(message)s'
            },
            'ghost': {
                'format': '%(asctime)s %(levelname)-8s %(name)-15s <%(session)s> %(message)s'
            }
        },
        'handlers': {
            'console': {
                'class': 'logging.StreamHandler',
                'formatter': 'default',
            },
            'console-ghost': {
                'class': 'logging.StreamHandler',
                'formatter': 'ghost',
            }
        },
        'loggers': {
            'ghost.session': {
                'handlers': ['console-ghost'],
                'propagate': False,
            },
        },
        'root': {
            'handlers': ['console'],
            'level':  'DEBUG',
        },
    })
```

This example is not a perfect replacement for the previous code but just demonstrate how the logging can now be customized to anyone's pleasure.

See https://github.com/fluent/fluent-logger-python for example of how someone would create a formatter class to do something else with the LogRecord.

This is re pull request (this one https://github.com/jrief/django-admin-sortable2/pull/88) , 
with tabs fixes, and Django+South notes


 @jrief , btw, thank you, what drew attention to tabs. I do not realize this mistake for a long time.

I suggest we expose something like this on the Python side for plugins:

```python
config.add_api_capability("identifier", description="", documentation="")
```
> It would raise an error if already defined for example


And shown in the root URL as a mapping:

```js
{
  "auth-fxa": {
    "description": "Firefox Account authentication",
    "documentation": "http://github.com/mozilla-services/cliquet-fxa"
  }
}
```

@almet @n1k0 @Natim thoughts?
